'''Lisbeth Berg-Hansen''' (born 14 March 1963) is a Norwegian businessperson and politician for the [[Norwegian Labour Party|Labour Party]].

She chaired the [[Norwegian Seafood Federation]] from 2002 to 2005, and was Vice President of the [[Confederation of Norwegian Enterprise]] from 2004 to 2008. In politics, she was a political advisor in the [[Norwegian Ministry of Fisheries|Ministry of Fisheries]] from 1992 to 1996, and [[State Secretary#Norway|State Secretary]] in the [[Norwegian Office of the Prime Minister|Office of the Prime Minister]] from 2000 to 2001.<ref name="hvem">{{cite book |title=Hvem er hvem? |last= |first= |authorlink= |year=2008 |editor=[[Knut Olav Åmås]] |publisher=Aschehoug |location=Oslo |isbn=978-82-03-23561-0 |page=55 }}</ref> On 20 October 2009, she was appointed [[Minister of Fisheries and Coastal Affairs (Norway)|Minister of Fisheries and Coastal Affairs]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/smk/Press-Center/Press-releases/2009/changes-in-the-government.html?id=582233 |title=Changes in the Government |author=[[Norwegian Office of the Prime Minister]] |date=20 October 2009 |accessdate=20 October 2009}}</ref>

She is the [[Chair (official)|deputy chair]] of the board of the [[Norwegian Institute of Marine Research]], and a member of the board of [[Aker Seafoods]], [[Fosen Trafikklag]], [[Investinor]] (formerly known as Statens Investeringsselskap), [[SOS-barnebyer]]<ref name=hvem/> and [[Bodø University College]].<ref>[http://www.innovasjonnorge.no/Aktuelt_fs/Nyheter/2008/Mars/statens_investeringsselskapAS_mars2008.pdf Board of directors of Investinor]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

She lives in [[Bindal]].<ref name="hvem" />

==Conflict of interest==
Berg-Hansen owns an 8% stake in [[:no:SinkabergHansen|SinkabergHansen AS]], one of Norway's salmon farms, through Jmj Invest AS.<ref>[http://www.proff.no/roller/jmj-invest-as/bindalseidet/-/Z0IC1GFG/ ]{{dead link|date=December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://e24.no/bedrift/976543718/sinkaberg-hansen-as/vikna|title=SINKABERG-HANSEN AS|website=E24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theforeigner.no/pages/news/norway-researchers-toxic-salmon-warning-creates-waves/|title=Norway researchers' toxic salmon warning creates waves|first=Michael|last=Sandelson|date=26 October 2018|website=theforeigner.no}}</ref>

[[Norges Miljøvernforbund|NMF]], a Norwegian environmental group, filed charges against Berg-Hansen in 2009 claiming that her own economic interests prompted her to violate the regulations she’s supposed to enforce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsinenglish.no/2009/11/25/critics-try-to-reel-in-fisheries-minister/|title=Critics try to reel in Fisheries Minister|website=www.newsinenglish.no}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nmf.no/underside.aspx?articleid=2355&pageId=14&news=1 ]{{dead link|date=December 2018}}</ref>

In November 2013 a [[France 2]] documentary accused Berg-Hansen of relaxing the legal levels of toxins allowed in fish in Norway while at the top of health advisory committees and related research institutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://openminds.swissre.com/stories/505/|title=Is fish farming the worst player in the food industry?|publisher=}}</ref>

